This paper proposes a neural model for extractive document summarization, which falls under the natural language processing (NLP) domain. Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The model also involves latent variables and training with gold summaries, which are common techniques in machine learning and artificial intelligence (AI), making cs.AI the second likely sub-category. The model is trained using a loss function, which is a common approach in machine learning and deep learning, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) a likely sub-category as well. The model also involves information retrieval (IR) techniques, such as selecting relevant sentences from a document, making cs.IR a possible sub-category. Finally, the model involves neural networks, which is a common technique in neural engineering (NE), making cs.NE a possible sub-category.
